2. What each Pantheon module does

A. Input Normalizer

Turns messy input into a common internal form.

Examples:
	•	text → semantic intent
	•	image → visual descriptors + embedding
	•	audio → transcript + prosody tags
	•	sensor/tool data → structured event objects

Think:
x \rightarrow \hat{x}
where \hat{x} is the shared intermediate representation.

⸻

B. Router

Decides which subsystem should handle which part.

Example:
	•	“What’s in this image?” → VLM first
	•	“Summarize this contract” → LLM + retrieval
	•	“Book this meeting” → LLM + calendar tool
	•	“Diagnose this UI issue from screenshot” → VLM + code agent + LLM

Formal:
R(\hat{x}) = \{m_1, m_2, ..., m_k\}

where m_i are selected modules.

⸻

C. Translator

This is the key.

Different systems emit different things:
	•	LLM → text / logits / tool calls
	•	VLM → visual embeddings / captions
	•	agent → action plans
	•	retrieval → documents / chunks
	•	segmentation model → masks / regions

The translator maps all of those into a shared schema.

Example shared schema:

{
  "intent": "answer_visual_question",
  "entities": ["person", "screen", "diagram"],
  "evidence": [
    {"type": "caption", "value": "chart with 8 AI model classes"},
    {"type": "ocr_text", "value": "LLMs are AI models..."},
    {"type": "retrieval_chunk", "value": "..."}
  ],
  "candidate_actions": [],
  "confidence": 0.81
}

So Pantheon becomes a semantic interlingua.

⸻

D. Combinator

This merges outputs from multiple specialists into one result.

Example:
	•	VLM says: “diagram of AI architectures”
	•	LLM says: “these categories are partly correct but a bit simplified”
	•	retrieval says: “here’s the official terminology”
	•	tool agent says: “I can generate a revised chart”

The combinator fuses them.

Formal:
C(y_1, y_2, ..., y_k) \rightarrow y^*

where y^* is the best merged interpretation.

This is where your “purple from red and blue” idea lives.

⸻

E. Memory / State

Keeps continuity across turns and across workflows.

Types:
	•	short-term working state
	•	session memory
	•	durable user/project memory
	•	provenance log

State example:

{
  "user_goal": "design Pantheon MVP",
  "chosen_stack": ["LLM", "VLM", "tool router"],
  "constraints": ["grounded", "modular", "buildable now"],
  "open_questions": ["shared schema", "evaluation strategy"]
}


⸻

F. Constraint Engine

This is the discipline layer.

It checks:
	•	consistency
	•	policy / safety
	•	reversibility
	•	resource limits
	•	uncertainty thresholds
	•	provenance requirements

Formal:
K(y^*, S, G) \rightarrow \{\text{allow, revise, block, escalate}\}

Where:
	•	S = state
	•	G = governance / constraints

This is your real-world Mirror / Checksum function.

⸻

G. Output Synthesizer

Turns the internal merged result into the final thing:
	•	answer
	•	action plan
	•	API call
	•	artifact
	•	refusal
	•	clarification request

